<br>
These events are very much similar to regular events, but are considered much more dangerous due to the unexpected strength of the enemies, as opposed to the somewhat regularity of npc enemies. Therefore it is VITAL that everyone acts according to the rules set forth in the event description and given by the raid leader. It is also vital for this kind of events that the raid leader has more than one option / route for entering and leaving the designated area of combat.<br>
<br>
These are the general rules the Bringers of Retribution are required to follow when engaging in PvP combat. These rules supersede all specific event rules, and are ALWAYS in place whenever a Bringer of Retribution engages another player in combat:<br>
<br>
- Do NOT farm greenies; We do not attack newbie areas specifically to kill newbies. Newbies who engage us in combat when we pass through or fight their brethren are allowable kills though.<br>
<br>
- Do NOT corpse camp; we do not corpse camp people, and we support the loot and scoot rule. If an enemy is slain, let them recover their corpse and leave by the fastest route possible. This often mean dragging their corpses away.. if there is a road open to do so, looting it where it fell is not considered part of our free pass, as there is no reason for the enemy to do so there. Enemies known to corpse camp themselves may be corpse camped for the duration of our attack on a location, but be certain it is the right person. Special events, namely attacks on zones, may also warrant the attack of anyone, even those who venture for their corpses, though often we will try to let them get their corpses and scoot instead.<br>
<br>
- Do  NOT train your own team ! We do not train our own team to claim camp sites, with one notable exception: those goods who train goods for this purpose can be forced out using any means available.<br>
<br>
These rules are our main rules of engagement and should be followed as closely as possible. Sometimes though they are there to be sent aside shortly (not put away), such as if we make a raid on the zone of Lake of Ill Omen, which support alot of newbie players. Upon reaching out striking area, and starting the raid, we can issue a zone warning that iksars will be killed on sight if seen outside the Cabilis ruins (they will learn anyways), and after such a warning has been issued we would kill even green ones who are seen outside it.. in this case the raid purpose itself forces us to change the PvP rule against greenies slightly, but not set it completely aside.<br>
<br>
As when posting raids against npcs, as many details as possibly should be posted in the raid description. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub86.ezboard.com/ukyrakasa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kyrakasa</A> at: 1/18/02 2:11:21 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#fff09d>- </font><a href=http://pub86.ezboard.com/bbringersofretribution>Wolves of Retribution</a><font color=#fff09d> - </font><a href=http://pub86.ezboard.com/fbringersofretributionfrm16>The Book of Retribution</a> <font color=#fff09d> - </font><a href="http://everquest.station.sony.com/stats/sz_summary.jsp">Official Sullon Zek PvP Points Page</a><font color=#fff09d> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.3<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

